
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Knowledge Transfer in Intraorganizational Networks: Effects of Network Position and Absorptive Capacity on Business Unit Innovation and Performance
AU  - Tsai, Wenpin
Y1  - 2001/10/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069443
DO  - 10.5465/3069443
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 996
EP  - 1004
VL  - 44
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Drawing on a network perspective on organizational learning, I argue that organizational units can produce more innovations and enjoy better performance if they occupy central network positions that provide access to new knowledge developed by other units. This effect, however, depends on units' absorptive capacity, or ability to successfully replicate new knowledge. Data from 24 business units in a petrochemical company and 36 business units in a food-manufacturing company show that the interaction between absorptive capacity and network position has significant, positive effects on business unit innovation and performance.
AB  - Drawing on a network perspective on organizational learning, I argue that organizational units can produce more innovations and enjoy better performance if they occupy central network positions that provide access to new knowledge developed by other units. This effect, however, depends on units' absorptive capacity, or ability to successfully replicate new knowledge. Data from 24 business units in a petrochemical company and 36 business units in a food-manufacturing company show that the interaction between absorptive capacity and network position has significant, positive effects on business unit innovation and performance.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/3069443
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/3069443
Y2  - 2026/04/24
