TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Influence of Demographic Heterogeneity on the Emergence and Consequences of Cooperative Norms in Work Teams
AU  - Chatman, Jennifer A.
AU  - Flynn, Francis J.
Y1  - 2001/10/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069440
DO  - 10.5465/3069440
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 956
EP  - 974
VL  - 44
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Drawing from social categorization theory, we found that greater demographic heterogeneity led to group norms emphasizing lower cooperation among student teams and officers from ten business units of a financial services firm. This effect faded over time. Perceptions of team norms among those more demographically different from their work group changed more, becoming more cooperative, as a function of contact with other members. Finally, cooperative norms mediated the relationship between group composition and work outcomes.
AB  - Drawing from social categorization theory, we found that greater demographic heterogeneity led to group norms emphasizing lower cooperation among student teams and officers from ten business units of a financial services firm. This effect faded over time. Perceptions of team norms among those more demographically different from their work group changed more, becoming more cooperative, as a function of contact with other members. Finally, cooperative norms mediated the relationship between group composition and work outcomes.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/3069440
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/3069440
Y2  - 2026/04/24
